USE practice_db;

-- Create user
CREATE USER 'student1'@'localhost'
IDENTIFIED BY 'pass123';

-- Give SELECT permission
GRANT SELECT
ON practice_db.students
TO 'student1'@'localhost';

-- Give INSERT and UPDATE permissions
GRANT INSERT, UPDATE
ON practice_db.students
TO 'student1'@'localhost';

-- Show granted permissions
SHOW GRANTS FOR 'student1'@'localhost';

-- Remove UPDATE permission
REVOKE UPDATE
ON practice_db.students
FROM 'student1'@'localhost';

-- Reload privileges
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

==========

DCL (Data Control Language) in SQL

DCL is used to control access permissions in a database.

Main DCL Commands:

Command	Purpose
GRANT	Give permission to users
REVOKE	Remove permission from users
Create Sample User
CREATE USER 'student1'@'localhost'
IDENTIFIED BY 'pass123';
1. GRANT Command

Used to give permissions.

Give SELECT Permission
GRANT SELECT
ON practice_db.students
TO 'student1'@'localhost';
Meaning
User can only view data
Cannot INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
Check Permission
SHOW GRANTS FOR 'student1'@'localhost';
2. GRANT Multiple Permissions
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE
ON practice_db.students
TO 'student1'@'localhost';
3. Give Permission on Entire Database
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES
ON practice_db.*
TO 'student1'@'localhost';
Meaning

User gets:

SELECT
INSERT
UPDATE
DELETE
CREATE
DROP
ALTER

on all tables inside practice_db.

Reload Privileges
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

4. REVOKE Command

Used to remove permissions.

Remove INSERT Permission

REVOKE INSERT
ON practice_db.students
FROM 'student1'@'localhost';

Remove All Permissions
REVOKE ALL PRIVILEGES
ON practice_db.*
FROM 'student1'@'localhost';

=========

| DCL Command | Description    |
| ----------- | -------------- |
| GRANT       | Gives access   |
| REVOKE      | Removes access |


